               <msContents>
                  <msItem xml:id="MS_Eng_hist_b_229-item1">
                     <locus from="1" to="10">(fols. 1–10)</locus>
                     <title key="work_12408">Inventory of the goods and chattels of <persName key="person_2520"><!-- not in VIAF -->Simon Burley</persName> in <placeName key="place_7011781">London</placeName></title>
                     <note>(including details of goods delivered to others as security for debts)</note>
                     <rubric>
                        <locus from="1" to="1">(fol. 1)</locus>
                        <gap reason="damage"/>Simon de Burley ordeina affaire son Inuentorie le viij iour de Nouembre lan | <gap reason="damage"/>sir Symond auoit sibien a le Meawes come a Baynardes Castell en Loundres les | ... </rubric>
                     <note>The heading matches that of the inventory of Burley's goods in National Archives, <bibl type="ms">
                           <ref target="http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C3680080">E 154/1/19</ref>
                        </bibl>, as printed by M. Clarke, <title>Fourteenth-Century Studies</title> (Oxford, 1937), 119 n., and the present MS. appears to be a duplicate of that roll. Both rolls are unprinted although an extract, a list of twenty-one books owned by Burley, was published from the TNA document by V. J. Scattergood, 'Two medieval book lists', <title>The Library</title> 5th ser. 23, 237.</note>
                     <!-- Inventory of goods of Simon de Burley at Barnard's castle, London, with four bonds from his debtors, 3-10 Ric II(5 mm) - French and Latin (TNA record) -->
                     <!-- f. 10r: refers to 25 Nov. 11R2. Dorse: note of delivery by 'John Emle hereford thes' angl' 2 Oct. 12R2-->
                     <note>Fols. 11–16, 19–30v, 31r-v, 33r are 18th (?)-19th cent. transcripts of the preceding. Fols. 16v-18v, 32r-v blank. Fols. 36r-42, 19th-cent. notes on Simon Burley and the Burley family.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="xno">Anglo-Norman (later notes in Latin, French and English)</textLang>
                  </msItem>
